{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17639236","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17639236"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:04:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:04:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17767"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17767","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17767"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.86,0.07,0,0.03,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10481"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72375"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10481","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10481"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17767"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57845"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"527"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24463"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24465"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24520"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72375","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72375"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-day history of abdominal pain. She describes the pain as initially around the belly button but now localises to the right lower quadrant. She also reports fever and nausea. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 120/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. Abdominal examination reveals tenderness at McBurney\u0027s point with guarding. Laboratory investigations show an elevated white blood cell count with neutrophilia.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Appendicitis","Cholecystitis","Diverticulitis","Gastroenteritis","Ovarian torsion"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Eappendicitis\u003C/strong\u003E. The initial periumbilical pain that localises to the right lower quadrant, along with fever and elevated white blood cell count, are classic signs. Tenderness at McBurney\u0027s point, further supports this diagnosis. McBurney\u0027s point is defined as the area one-third of the distance from the anterior superior iliac spine towards the umbilicus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECholecystitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with right upper quadrant pain, often associated with nausea and vomiting, and tenderness in the right upper quadrant. This is not consistent with the patient\u0027s symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiverticulitis\u003C/strong\u003E usually presents with left lower quadrant pain, fever, and leukocytosis, which does not match the right lower quadrant pain described here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGastroenteritis\u003C/strong\u003E often presents with diffuse abdominal pain, diarrhoea, and vomiting, without the localised tenderness or elevated white blood cell count seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOvarian torsion\u003C/strong\u003E can present with sudden onset lower abdominal pain, but it is often associated with adnexal tenderness and may have a different clinical picture than described here.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Appendicitis often presents with initial periumbilical pain that later localises to the right lower quadrant.","Fever and elevated white blood cell count with neutrophilia are common findings in appendicitis."],"references":["Humes DJ, Simpson J. Acute appendicitis. BMJ. 2006 Sep 9;333(7567):530-4. doi: 10.1136/bmj.38940.664363.AE. PMID: 16960208; PMCID: PMC1562475.","Alvarado, A. How to improve the clinical diagnosis of acute appendicitis in resource limited settings. World J Emerg Surg 11, 16 (2016). https://doi.org/10.1186/s13017-016-0071-8","Di Saverio S, Podda M, De Simone B, et al. Diagnosis and treatment of acute appendicitis: 2020 update of the WSES Jerusalem guidelines. World J Emerg Surg. 2020 Apr 15;15(1):27. doi: 10.1186/s13017-020-00306-3. PMID: 32295644; PMCID: PMC7386163.","Petroianu A. Diagnosis of acute appendicitis. Int J Surg. 2012;10(3):115-9. doi: 10.1016/j.ijsu.2012.02.006. Epub 2012 Feb 17. PMID: 22349155."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57845"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17767"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57845","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57845"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-21T10:17:45+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-21T10:20:06+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10481"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72375"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroup